Defines the process-execution boundary that `crate::checks` runs external tools through, keeping check logic pure and unit-testable offline (mirrors `ctx-context`'s `Env` seam pattern).

`CommandOutcome` captures exit code (`Option<i32>`), lossy-UTF8 stdout/stderr; `ok()` returns true only when `code == Some(0)` — a `None` code (killed by signal) counts as not-ok.

`Runner` trait's `run(&self, tool: &str, args: &[&str], envs: &[(&str, &str)]) -> Result<CommandOutcome, CheckError>` is the sole entry point checks depend on; real code uses `ProcRunner`, tests substitute a fake implementing the same trait to inject canned output/errors without spawning processes.

`ProcRunner::run` maps `std::io::ErrorKind::NotFound` specifically to `CheckError::ToolMissing(tool)`, distinguishing "binary not on PATH" from any other spawn/wait failure (`CheckError::Spawn { tool, detail }`). Non-zero exit codes are not treated as errors here — they surface via `CommandOutcome::ok()`/`code`, letting callers in `checks` decide what a given tool's exit status means.